The Fetishists of Free Trade
From Cambridge —— Recently, I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course at Harvard, taught by two of my colleagues. "I must warn you,"
one of them told me in advance: "These students are strong advocates of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and more than 90% favored the former.
And this was before he had even begun to teach the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that asking the same question in real surveys of representative samples — rather than Harvard students — would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers of Harvard students would not be particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technology and better education tend to be more inclined to support free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students had already expected their future (financial) prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they simply do not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different form, emphasizing the distributional effects that trade might produce.
The consensus in favor of fair trade completely disappeared, even more quickly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked everyone whether they agreed with me on a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers, and then told them that I had a way to make $200 disappear from Nicholas's account — poof! — while increasing John's account by $300, and through this social engineering feat, the class as a whole would gain an additional $100 in value.
Would they allow me to pull this little trick?
The result was that only a small portion firmly agreed, many were hesitant, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.

It is clearly evident that students find it difficult to tolerate such a significant redistribution of income, even when the overall economic pie has been made larger.
I then asked why most of them almost instinctively support free trade, which actually also leads to a similar — indeed even a greater — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students looked stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John both ran competing small businesses.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced better products, so he not only ended up $300 ahead of Nicholas, but also drove Nicholas's company out of the market, causing him a loss of $200.
How many students would support this change?
This time, the majority voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I immediately proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
What if John drove Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or by employing child labor in Indonesia?
This time, the level of agreement with the change decreased sequentially with the above options.
Furthermore, technological innovation can also, like trade, leave certain groups in a more disadvantaged position — what is your view on this?
Very few students were willing to restrain the development of technology.
For almost everyone, it would be a foolish idea to ban the production of light bulbs in order to protect the jobs of candle makers.
Therefore, the students are not necessarily opposed to redistribution, but only to certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they care about the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the outcomes of redistribution, we must know the objective context that gives rise to such outcomes.
We do not resent the enormous wealth of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett, even though some of their competitors have not fared well, probably because they and their competitors all operate according to the same fundamental rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become rich not through their own intelligence and effort, but through fraud, violation of labor laws, environmental destruction, or by exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be entirely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution that is achieved by violating widely observed moral norms within our own country, how can we feel justified when it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to equalize in the long run, and everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely to not mind the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that despite the short-term negative consequences technology may bring to some people, we are still willing to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group of people — low-educated blue-collar workers — we become deeply concerned about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute concerns about globalization to foolish, selfish trade protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Because they fail to recognize that international trade — although not often — sometimes leads to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists are also unable to appropriately engage in public discourse.
And if they are morally indefensible, how can they vigorously defend trade?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond by restricting trade.
There are many pros and cons that need to be carefully weighed, including the possibility that globalization may cause more severe wealth deprivation for people in other places than for victims in the United States itself.
However, democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this issue and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions.
And that kind of obsessive attachment to globalization simply because it has made the pie bigger will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
